Cindy Sheehan, a grieving mother who lost her son in Iraq, demands answers from President Bush.
She questions the purpose of the war and the needless deaths it has caused.
She seeks closure and accountability, refusing to leave until she speaks with Bush directly.
She has garnered support nationwide, becoming a symbol of the anti-war movement.
Despite resistance from the White House, she remains steadfast in her quest for peace and justice.
She embodies the pain and frustration of families who have lost loved ones in the conflict, urging the administration to acknowledge their sacrifices and end the war.
